<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08041b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08041b">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08041b"> 41(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> occasion &agrave; saisir</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Le plus &eacute;pais bandeau de l&apos;aveuglement est peut-&ecirc;tre celui de l&apos;app&eacute;tition, mais quand le d&eacute;sir est satisfait ou s&apos;il tarde trop &agrave; l&apos;&ecirc;tre, les liens du bandeau se rel&acirc;chent, et il tombe pitieusement sans qu&apos;on songe &agrave; le relever. C&apos;est pourquoi les canailles sont toujours si press&eacute;es quand elles proposent une mauvaise affaire. Elles ont surpris notre envie et elles l&apos;exaltent par des promesses trompeuses au niveau de nos esp&eacute;rances. Sachant bien qu&apos;&agrave; la r&eacute;flexion notre go&ucirc;t risque de se modifier, elles brusquent l&apos;attaque: &ldquo;H&acirc;tez-vous&hellip; <mark>occasion &agrave; saisir</mark> &hellip; r&eacute;ponse t&eacute;l&eacute;graphique&hellip;&rdquo; <br><font color="green">[The greatest blindfold may well be that of appetition [the direction of desire towards an object]</font>, but when desire has been satisfied or when it has remained too long unsatisfied, the ties of the blindfold are loosened, and it falls pitifully without anyone trying to put it back. That is why the canaille are so pressed for time when they try to dupe us. They have discovered our desire and they flatter it with their deceptive promises answering to our hopes. Knowing full well that if we think about it, we will change our mind, they go for a surprise attack: &ldquo;Hurry up ... seize the chance ... reply by telegram ...&rdquo;] <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 304</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
